project:
Earth rotates on its axis every 23.9 hours. 
                                                                 
The Moon orbits the Earth every 27.3 days.
                                                                 
And Earth revolves about the Sun every 365 days.
I learned that EVERYTHING IS ROTATING!

Step 1: Find the telescope.                                     Step 2: Find the photos.                                           Step 3: Find the special glasses.                               Step 4: Head to your spacecraft :)                                 Step 5: Sleep.
Let's go see an eclipse together!
I want to tell you many things about eclipses!

Hey, Saros! 
You finally woke up.
Interesting things have been happening with planet Earth, the moon and the sun while you were sleeping, would you like to know?
I haven't heard from you in a long time.

The moon is 400 times smaller than the Sun. 
                                                                 
But because the Sun is 400 times farther away, they appear to be the same size in the sky.

Did you like my telescope?                                         
I love looking at the moon with it.
Astronomers first have to work out the geometry and mechanics of how Earth and the Moon orbit the Sun to determine when and where eclipses will occur.
To see a solar eclipse, you need to use special glasses to see the sun. SUNGLASSES DO NOT WORK
Well, see you at another eclipse, Saros! Well, in another 18 years 11 days and 8 hours.
Do you want to go back to sleep already?
Learn more about eclipses at science.nasa.gov/eclipses/
